message.content:
We can calculate the requested ratios step‐by‐step. Note that when needed we use the end-of‐period figures (or the averages when required).

──────────────────────────────
Step 1. Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio

• From the cash flow statement, the net cash flow from operating activities is –5,714,107.45.
• From the balance sheet, the end number for Total Current Liabilities is 2,736,025.72.
• Ratio = (Operating Cash Flow) / (Current Liabilities) 
    = –5,714,107.45 / 2,736,025.72 
    ≈ –2.09

──────────────────────────────
Step 2. Debt to Equity Ratio

• Total Liabilities are the “Total Current Liabilities”. (There are no non-current liabilities provided.) So use 2,736,025.72.
• Total Owner’s Equity at period end is 11,330,150.23.
• Ratio = (Total Liabilities) / (Total Owner’s Equity) 
    = 2,736,025.72 / 11,330,150.23 
    ≈ 0.24

──────────────────────────────
Step 3. Total Asset Turnover Ratio

• Total Revenue for the period is 6,920,513.79 (from the income statement).
• To compute average total assets:
  Beginning Total Assets (2023-12-31) = 13,000,000.00
  Ending Total Assets (2024-01-31) = 14,066,175.95
  Average Total Assets = (13,000,000.00 + 14,066,175.95) / 2 
              = 27,066,175.95 / 2 
              ≈ 13,533,087.98
• Ratio = Total Revenue / Average Total Assets 
     = 6,920,513.79 / 13,533,087.98 
     ≈ 0.51

──────────────────────────────
Step 4. Quick Ratio

The Quick Ratio is defined as (Quick Assets) / (Current Liabilities) where “Quick Assets” usually include cash and cash equivalents, short-term receivables (and other receivables) but exclude inventory.

• Cash & cash equivalents from the balance sheet:
  Cash on Hand = 735,892.55
  Bank Deposits = 103,027.27
  Interest Receivable = 2,566.71
  Accounts Receivable = 2,923,459.19
  Sum of Quick Assets = 735,892.55 + 103,027.27 + 2,566.71 + 2,923,459.19
                  = 3,764,945.72
• Current Liabilities = 2,736,025.72
• Ratio = 3,764,945.72 / 2,736,025.72 ≈ 1.38

──────────────────────────────
Step 5. Operating Cash Flow Ratio

This ratio is often defined the same as (Operating Cash Flow) / (Current Liabilities). Therefore, it is the same number as calculated in Step 1.

• Ratio = –5,714,107.45 / 2,736,025.72 ≈ –2.09

──────────────────────────────
Step 6. Return on Equity (ROE)

ROE is calculated as Net Profit divided by average owner’s equity.

• Net Profit from the income statement is –1,669,849.77.
• Owner’s Equity levels:
  Beginning Owner’s Equity (2023-12-31) = 13,000,000.00 
  Ending Owner’s Equity (2024-01-31) = 11,330,150.23
  Average Owner’s Equity = (13,000,000.00 + 11,330,150.23) / 2 
          = 24,330,150.23 / 2 
          ≈ 12,165,075.12
• ROE = (Net Profit) / (Average Owner’s Equity)
     = –1,669,849.77 / 12,165,075.12 
     ≈ –0.1373, or –13.73%

──────────────────────────────
Step 7. Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio

This ratio is usually taken as “Total Revenue” divided by “Average Accounts Receivable”. Assuming sales are on credit:

• Accounts Receivable at beginning (2023-12-31) = 0.00 
• Accounts Receivable at end (2024-01-31) = 2,923,459.19
• Average Accounts Receivable = (0.00 + 2,923,459.19) / 2 ≈ 1,461,729.60
• Ratio = Total Revenue / Average Accounts Receivable 
     = 6,920,513.79 / 1,461,729.60 
     ≈ 4.73

──────────────────────────────
Thus, our final answers are:

{
  "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-2.09",
  "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.24",
  "Total Asset Turnover Ratio": "0.51",
  "Quick Ratio": "1.38",
  "Operating Cash Flow Ratio": "-2.09",
  "Return on Equity (ROE)": "-13.73%",
  "Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio": "4.73"
}
